  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concern—it's something I've seen play out in my own life and the lives of my neighbors. As an electrician who's worked on everything from household wiring to industrial systems, I've often encountered people who seem to hesitate or doubt their abilities because of what they believe about their group. My father, a PhD holder, always told me that the best way to learn is to practice, but I've seen how stereotypes can make even those who are capable feel discouraged. For instance, when I was younger, I remember a friend who was a girl and wanted to pursue engineering. She told me she felt nervous about being in a class where everyone else seemed to know more than her. That's stereotype threat: the fear that your group is less capable, which affects your performance. I think we should address it, but not with big, sweeping policies that might not reach those who need it most. Instead, we can start by creating environments where people feel safe to ask questions and make mistakes. In my shop, I've noticed that when we take time to explain things patiently and celebrate small victories, everyone feels more confident. This is especially important for women and people of color, who often face stereotypes that they aren't as good at math or science. But the key is to do it without making it about the group, but about the individual. It's not about changing the system overnight—it's about building trust and understanding one person at a time. I believe that by focusing on practical, hands-on learning and fostering a sense of community, we can help everyone thrive in STEM.",
